TITLE Use Functional setState Updates
USE FUNCTIONAL SETSTATE UPDATES
When updating state based on the current state value, UT functional update form of setState IO directly referencing the state variable. This prevents stale closures, eliminates unnecessary dependencies, and creates stable callback references. 
Incorrect (requires state as dependency): 
CODE tsx 599CHARS
The first callback is recreated every time items changes, which can cause child components to re-render unnecessarily. The second callback has a stale closure bug—it will always reference the initial items value. 
Correct (stable callbacks, no stale closures): 
CODE tsx 531CHARS
Benefits: 
Stable callback references - Callbacks don't need to be recreated when state changes No stale closures - Always operates on the latest state value Fewer dependencies - Simplifies dependency arrays and reduces memory leaks Prevents bugs - Eliminates the most common source of React closure bugs 
WTU functional updates: 
Any setState that depends on the current state value Inside useCallback/useMemo when state is needed Event handlers that reference state Async operations that update state 
When direct updates are fine: 
SETTING_STATE_TO_A_STATIC_VALUE `setCount(0)`
Note: IYPH React Compiler enabled, the compiler can automatically optimize some cases, but functional updates are still recommended for correctness and to prevent stale closure bugs. 